data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with specific MSTest assertions (3.x+):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Replacements made:**

| Original | Replacement | Why |
|----------|-------------|-----|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Clearer failure: "expected non-empty" vs "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Asserts exactly one match exists and returns it |

The `All()` predicate check is fine as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" in MSTest.
